          "body": "Verses 4 and 5 present the psalm's sharpest binary. The petition of verse 4 — 'Do good, O LORD, to those who are good and to those who are upright in heart' — is not a request for God to bless everyone regardless of character. The prayer is morally calibrated: it intercedes for the good and the upright, those whose hearts (*libbah*) are aligned with Yahweh's moral character. This is not works-righteousness; it is covenant faithfulness — the 'good' of verse 4 is those who have remained loyal to the LORD while the scepter pressed upon them. Verse 5 then names the other group: those who turn aside (*natah*) to crooked ways (*aqalqal* — the most twisted word in the psalm's vocabulary). These are not pagans outside the covenant; the verse implies people within Israel who, under the pressure of the scepter, have chosen the winding path of accommodation. Their fate is to be led away with the very evildoers whose scepter they accommodated. The judgment is symmetrical: you aligned with the crooked; you are gathered with the crooked. The closing benediction — 'Peace be upon Israel' — then pronounces shalom over the covenant-faithful community, not as a contradiction of the judgment but as its complement. The psalm ends on the side of the trustful, the good, the upright — for them, the entire argument resolves into shalom."
