          "body": "Psalm 125 resonates across the canon in three directions. The immovable Zion of verse 1 echoes Psalm 46:5 ('God is in the midst of her, she will not be moved') and Isaiah 28:16 ('the one who trusts will not be disturbed'). The 'scepter of wickedness' in verse 3 stands in deliberate canonical contrast to the messianic scepter of Psalm 2:9 and the righteous scepter of Psalm 45:6 — the wicked scepter is temporary and bounded; the Messiah's scepter is eternal and just. Peter Craigie (Psalms 1-50, Word Biblical Commentary) and others note that the Songs of Ascents read as a whole move toward the eschatological shalom of Psalm 134; Psalm 125's 'peace be upon Israel' anticipates that final destination. In the New Testament, Paul picks up the identical encirclement language in Philippians 4:7 — 'the peace of God... will guard your hearts and your minds in Christ Jesus' — the same total-surrounding protection, now explicitly mediated through the One who is Himself the peace of God. The theological movement from Psalm 125 to Philippians 4 is not a stretch; it is the canonical line from promise to fulfillment, from Yahweh surrounding Zion's pilgrims to the peace of God standing guard over every believer in every city of the empire."
